

Primary & Foreign Keys Key Structure Explained:

Primary Key (PK): A unique identifier for each record in a table.
Foreign Key (FK): A column in one table that references the PK in another table, enforcing relationships.
One-to-Many (1:M): One record in Table A relates to many records in Table B.
One-to-One (1:1): One record in Table A relates to exactly one record in Table B.
Self-Referencing (1:M self): A table references itself through its own PK.

-----

Table-by-Table Overview

customers
PK: customer_id
Relationships:
order_transactions.customer_id is an FK referencing customers.customer_id (1 customer → many orders).

-------------

order_transactions


PK: order_transaction_id
FKs:
customer_id → customers.customer_id
original_sale_transaction_id → order_transactions.order_transaction_id (self-reference)
Relationships:
1 customer → many orders
1 order → many order_line_items (order_line_items.order_transaction_id)
1 order → 1 marketing record (order_marketing_details.order_transaction_id)
1 original sale → many return transactions (self-reference)

--------------------
order_line_items


PK: transaction_line_item_id
FKs:
order_transaction_id → order_transactions.order_transaction_id
product_id → products.product_id
Relationships:
1 order → many line items
1 product → many line items

--------------------
products

PK: product_id
Relationships:
order_line_items.product_id is an FK referencing products.product_id (1 product can appear in many orders).

--------------------
order_marketing_detail

PK: row_id
FK: transaction_id → order_transactions.order_id
Relationships:
1 order → 1 marketing record

-------

Summary of Relationships:

customers → order_transactions (1:M)
order_transactions → order_line_items (1:M)
products → order_line_items (1:M)
order_transactions → order_marketing_details (1:1)
order_transactions → order_transactions (1:M self-reference)
